    {
        "content": "<p>Hi, I'm an undergraduate who's fairly new at Lean, so there may be some misunderstandings not only about the way Lean works but also about math. I've read most of \"Theorem Proving In Lean\" (\"Release 3.23.0\") and am trying to wrap my head around some code in mathlib.</p>\n<p>My current underlying goal is to write a proof of \"For any given normed vector space E and any strict subspace F (i.e. any subspace that is not equal to E), the interior of F in E is empty.\"</p>\n<p>I've looked at the <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/blob/d9767b5472a119ce6f34c3007cbcc0cb6a2f2326/src/analysis/normed_space/basic.lean\">code for normed spaces in mathlib</a>, and tried to start things from there, specifically looking at the proof of \"<a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/analysis/normed_space/basic.html#interior_closed_ball\">the interior of a closed ball is a ball</a>\" because it looks like the closest thing I could find from what I want to prove. But the whole file has bits that I don't understand. I started with this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"n\">analysis.normed_space.basic</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">variables</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"bp\">ùïÇ</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"o\">}</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">normed_field</span> <span class=\"bp\">ùïÇ</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">variables</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">E</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"o\">}</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">seminormed_add_comm_group</span> <span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">]</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">normed_space</span> <span class=\"bp\">ùïÇ</span> <span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">theorem</span> <span class=\"n\">strict_subspace_empty_interior</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">F</span><span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">submodule</span> <span class=\"bp\">ùïÇ</span> <span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">):</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">interior</span> <span class=\"n\">F</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">isempty</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n    <span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>But \"interior F\" is not defined since I defined F not as a set, but as a submodule of E. From <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/analysis/normed_space/basic.html#submodule.normed_space\">this</a> I gather that F <em>should</em> have some sort of normed space structure, but I don't really understand how to use it. Also, if I replace \"interior F\" with \"interior E\", it still doesn't work as a normed space doesn't seem to have an underlying set structure in mathlib. Now I think I understand that modules and stuff like that aren't always proper sets, but a normed space should be, since the norm is a blatant function from the space to the set of real numbers. Perhaps I missed something but I believe nothing in mathlib gives a set structure to normed spaces, so I'm a bit lost here.</p>\n<p>There will probably be more issues when I eventually try to complete the proof, but that's where I'm at currently. Please feel free to suggest any resources that I may have overlooked.</p>",
        "id": 317035102,
        "sender_full_name": "sty",
        "timestamp": 1671568500
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What happens if you write <code>interior (F : set E)</code> instead of <code>interior F</code>?</p>",
        "id": 317035456,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1671568627
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Note that you are missing the assumption that <code>F</code> is proper. You can add <code>(hF : F ‚â† ‚ä§)</code> to do that.</p>",
        "id": 317035517,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1671568658
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>‚ä§ = \\top</code> is the \"top element\".</p>",
        "id": 317035560,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1671568677
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"573729\">sty</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113488-general/topic/Trying.20to.20prove.3A.20any.20strict.20subspace.20has.20empty.20interior/near/317035102\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>... doesn't seem to have an underlying set structure in mathlib. Now I think I understand that modules and stuff like that aren't always proper sets, but a normed space should be, since the norm is a blatant function from the space to the set of real numbers. Perhaps I missed something but I believe nothing in mathlib gives a set structure to normed spaces, so I'm a bit lost here.</p>\n<p>There will probably be more issues when I eventually try to complete the proof, but that's where I'm at currently. Please feel free to suggest any resources that I may have overlooked.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Talking about a \"set structure\" doesn't have a precise meaning in Lean. But for all practical purpose these things are \"sets\" in the colloquial mathematical meaning of the word.<br>\nHowever, <code>interior</code> is only defined for terms of type <code>set X</code>, where <code>X</code> is topological space (strictly, a <code>Type</code> + instance of <code>topological_space</code>). Now this is maybe linguistically confusing, but <code>set X</code> means \"set of terms of type <code>X</code>\". In other words, <code>set X</code> is the \"powerset\" aka \"subsets of <code>X</code>\".</p>",
        "id": 317036161,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1671568869
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But <code>F</code> is a submodule of <code>E</code>, so Lean will know how to turn it into a \"subset\". You can do that by writing <code>(F : set E)</code>.</p>",
        "id": 317036210,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1671568897
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There is also a confusion about <code>is_empty</code>.</p>",
        "id": 317036763,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Massot",
        "timestamp": 1671569095
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thank you, that helps me a lot!</p>\n<p>Now, why is it needed to use <code>‚ä§</code>? I think I understand why <code>F ‚â† E</code> makes no sense (since <code>F</code> and <code>E</code> aren't the same type), but then what object does <code>‚ä§</code> really refer to?</p>\n<p>Also I've just figured out now that <code>submodule</code> does have a <code>carrier</code> property that gives a set, but <code>module</code> doesn't seem to. Why is that?</p>\n<p>And yes, there was a confusion about <code>is_empty</code>, I typed that from memory, thanks for pointing it out :D<br>\nHere's where I'm at now:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"n\">analysis.normed_space.basic</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">variables</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"bp\">ùïÇ</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"o\">}</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">normed_field</span> <span class=\"bp\">ùïÇ</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">variables</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">E</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"o\">}</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">seminormed_add_comm_group</span> <span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">]</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">normed_space</span> <span class=\"bp\">ùïÇ</span> <span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">theorem</span> <span class=\"n\">strict_subspace_empty_interior</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">F</span><span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">submodule</span> <span class=\"bp\">ùïÇ</span> <span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">):</span> <span class=\"n\">F</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚â†</span> <span class=\"bp\">‚ä§</span>  <span class=\"bp\">-&gt;</span> <span class=\"bp\">¬¨</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">interior</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">F</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">set</span> <span class=\"n\">E</span><span class=\"o\">))</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">nonempty</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n    <span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>The \"is not nonempty\" thing looks kind of weird to me, is there a cleaner way to write it?</p>",
        "id": 317037079,
        "sender_full_name": "sty",
        "timestamp": 1671569235
